It was -23¬∞C the night that we went ice swimming. My hands and feet froze to the ladder as I made my way into the pitch black water below. I'd been waiting for this moment the entire trip. Not because I have some strange love for cold water. I don't. ü•∂ But as usual, my curiosity got the best of me! People in Finland swear that regular cold water swimming increases both life expectancy and overall quality of life. It's also supposed  to give you a pretty nice endorphin high. Turns out, that's true - you just have to wait for the initial panic to pass! üòú

The photos from this day don‚Äôt lie, but they do tell an unexpected story. At a quick glance, most people assume this photo was taken on a moody PNW morning... The factor that I overlooked was the finiteness of time. The concept is invisible to a child. Kids may know logically that they will one day be old, but they can't feel it. It sounds like a rumor. The carefree timelessness of my youth was rattled in my 20s. A kind of panic set in. Time became visible. Each choice I made began to feel more and more final, as if every choice was the death of others. Millions of doors were closing behind me as I passed them in the hallway. Am I missing out? Am I making the right decisions? Am I becoming the person I want to be? It often dawns too late that we have only one life, only one path, and the choices we make become the story of our lives. // Jedidiah Jenkins

Photography wasn't the focus on this trip. Family was. For almost two weeks I hiked through the European Alps with my family this summer. It was something we had talked about doing for years, but life had other plans, and I never really thought it would happen anyway. Then, just when I'd almost forgotten about the whole idea, tickets were booked and it was happening. I don't know if it's the lack of service, the common struggle, or the sometimes long monotonous miles, but the trail has a way of bringing people together. I've learned a lot through travel, but perhaps the most unexpected lesson has been to not take family--however you chose  to define your family--for granted. Without them, there is no home to go back to.
-
Shot on @sonyalpha a7rII, 70mm, ISO 100, f/11. #alphacollective

node.text:
Life doesn‚Äôt always go the way we plan. When things fall apart it can seem overwhelming in the moment. It‚Äôs hard to see past the frustration, disappointment, heartbreak. But it‚Äôs pretty nuts to take a step back sometimes and realize that the best things in my life, the best people, have come out of some of my greatest failures, and my worst mistakes. I‚Äôm not sure that I believe everything happens for a reason, but I do know that if everything always worked out the way we wanted, we‚Äôd miss out on an awful lot of amazing moments.
-
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I was expecting a week of backpacking in the Sierras. But when Quin picked me up at the airport he asked how I would feel about hiking down to Havasupai with a bunch of strangers instead. Apparently someone had reached out to him with extra permits for the next day. Neither of us knew anything about the guy, and the idea of hiking into the desert with a random person sounded like the perfect beginning to a horror movie. But if you‚Äôve ever tried to get permits to Havasupai, you know that if someone offers them, you just say yes. 24 hours later I was laying next to this waterfall, looking out across one of the prettiest canyons out there, with four new friends. All I‚Äôm saying, is maybe, just maybe, it‚Äôs not such a bad idea to talk to strangers after all!
-
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I felt the cool sand seep up between my toes as it engulfed my feet. The sun was setting and the sky popped with color against the white horizon. I sat down to enjoy the show. When the last streak of orange had faded, darkness rolled in heavy with stars. The park was closed now and the sky felt a little too close. A crushing desire to internalize the moment washed over me. A need to capture it. To remember every detail. Something about the immensity of nature in places like this had always elicited an overwhelming mixture of loneliness and belonging. A hazy, yet unmistakable sense that I am part of something much larger. If only for a fleeting moment.

People always ask what travel has taught me. I‚Äôm pretty sure they are looking for something about the power of travel to bring us together. That through travel we discover truth; about the world, about others, and about ourselves - a proof of the promise that humankind is far more beautiful than it is kind. They want to hear that travel is a journey into yourself, after which you will never be the same. And that‚Äôs all true. But I think the far more important thing I‚Äôve learned is to appreciate where I am. Especially when I feel like I‚Äôm nowhere at all. Because like travel, life is impermanent. And at the end of the day I don‚Äôt miss the places I‚Äôve never seen, or the things I‚Äôve never experienced. I miss the slow moments. The details. @visitsouthtyrol #southtyrol

When I was little my dad went on a backpacking trip with a bunch of friends in Colorado‚Äôs San Juan Mountains. When he got home he looked a little skinnier, his beard was a little longer, and he'd clearly forgotten sunscreen. But what I remember the most was that he looked really happy. And after all these years I'm finally understanding why. It only took a day hiking through the San Juans to understand that this is the type of place that sticks with you long after you've returned home. #visitcolorado #bucketlist #sponsor #coloradolive

On a trip that was full of bumps and unexpected turns, it was nice to be able to rely on my @travelprointl Platinum¬Æ Elite carry-on to get me to the next destination smoothly. The new line is @travelprointl‚Äôs most premium collection, and they spared no detail when creating it. From the USB port that allows you to easily charge your phone on the go, to the organized compartments that make packing easier, the suitcase has it all! On a day when I thought that nothing could out shine the views, it was the people we met along the way that ended up stealing the show. I love the outdoors for the solitude it offers. For the respite from daily distractions. For the quiet. But I‚Äôve also grown to love the people it brings together. There‚Äôs something special about humans from all walks of life converging on one trail.

I'm not a competitive person. Or at least that's what I've always told myself. But I'm actually just terrified of failing. Growing up I convinced myself that if I didn't try, then I couldn't really lose. And for a long time that logic seemed to work out for me. I built an entire identity around it. I didn't let myself want anything. And in turn I didn't get hurt. It was that simple. Until it wasn't. Until I realized that not losing, isn't the same as winning. And not hurting is not the same as happiness. I'm still afraid to put myself out there. To acknowledge when I want something. To let myself try. But now I know that there are far worse things than failing - like never knowing.

We went straight to the water when we got to Lake Tahoe. I laid a towel out on one of the big rocks, and jumped right in! When I came back to shore my towel was no where to be found. And then I saw it - about five feet away, at the bottom of the lake. It was then that I remembered I had left my phone sitting on that towel. I looked again, and sure enough it was also hanging out at the bottom of the lake. So basically, what I‚Äôm trying to say, is that if you come to Tahoe, just know that the water is so beautiful that even your phone will try and jump in if you aren‚Äôt carful! The irony is, now that I‚Äôve traveled to some of the places I only dreamed about back in the day, I‚Äôve realized that you don‚Äôt have to travel half way around the world to experience a beautiful place. That was just an excuse I used to avoid living in the present. This road trip has been all about finding those memory making, life affirming, stunning locations, right in our own backyard. I‚Äôm more convinced than ever that there is beauty everywhere, if we just open our minds to it.

Last week I asked you guys if you had any questions you would like me to answer. One question that came up over and over again was, ‚Äúhow do I afford to travel all the time?‚Äù I posted my answer to that question in my newest blog. My goal was to be as transparent as possible about this topic. And I hope it answers at least some of your questions. But if you read it, and it feels like I am completely out of touch with your reality, that‚Äôs probably because I am. My experience is unique to me, and I can only share my story. In the end, that‚Äôs all each of us can do. And even though we are all different, by sharing our story, our diverse world views, and our experiences, we bridge the gap between those differences, and hopefully make this big world just a little bit smaller.

I had corrective eye surgery yesterday. I've worn contacts since I was 12, and without them I couldn't see much further than a few feet in front of me. Even then it was mostly just blurry shapes. So it was pretty surreal to open my eyes this morning and be able to see every detail in the room. I still can't quite wrap my mind around it. I take so many blessings for granted in my life. I forget to appreciate the little things - to live in the present moment. And I'm not sure why it took this relatively minor event in my life to remind me that happiness is found in the little stuff. In the right now. In gratitude. But I'm glad it did.

node.text: The farther one gets into the wilderness, the closer you get to yourself. A few months ago I was invited to Qu√©bec to let go from all the external distractions in my life. I left behind my phone, my camera, and social media. The experience was a much needed reminder of the freedom that comes from being untethered from technology. I didn‚Äôt know what to expect when I agreed to go on the trip. Qu√©bec was a relatively unknown location for me. But the experience really solidified my belief that there are few things more healing than wide open spaces where your mind has enough room to take flight. Qu√©bec is the type of place where you can find the freedom to listen without noise, to connect without service, and to live deliberately without distraction. It‚Äôs a place you really have to experience for yourself to truly appreciate. #QuebecOriginal @tourismequebec

I get a lot of messages asking me how to start doing ‚Äúwhat I do.‚Äù I never know how to answer, because I honestly have no idea what I‚Äôm doing. It‚Äôs cliche, but I think the best advice I could give is to just START - even if you don‚Äôt know exactly what it is that you‚Äôre starting! I‚Äôve come to realize in my own life that there is almost no such thing as ready. There is no perfect time. If I wait until I‚Äôm ready to do something, I will likely never do it.  Every day I have to force myself to not let perfect be the enemy of good. Understand that nothing happens over night, and rarely does anyone ever feel ready to take a leap of faith. Now is as good a time as any to start living the life you want, because it‚Äôs the only time we have any control over.

I‚Äôve always loved photography. I didn‚Äôt necessarily always take photos. But I was that little kid that would find the stack of old Nat Geo mags shoved in some ubiquitous dusty closet. It didn‚Äôt matter where I was, the photos in those magazines transported me to different worlds. I was captivated by the idea that an image could allow someone to experience an emotion, or moment in time, that they weren‚Äôt physically present for.  I wanted to be part of that world. But even as a kid, it was a dream that I wouldn't let myself take seriously. I couldn‚Äôt even bring myself to say it out loud. And if I‚Äôm being completely honest, I still can‚Äôt. Because the thing about dreams, is that their often aren‚Äôt defined paths to achieving them. No one size fits all. No instructions. And forging your own way can be terrifying. But here‚Äôs the thing; as time passes, life only becomes more complicated, responsibilities pile on, and decisions weigh a little heavier. As a result we rarely feel ready. There‚Äôs never a right time to put your dreams into motion. But there will always be right now. And now, is as good a time as any!

I'm sitting on a plane, about to fly home. I've only been home a few days over the past month or so. It wasn't a deliberate decision exactly. Nor was it a particularly responsible one. But life happens, opportunity knocks, dreams whisper, and at some point I made a subconscious decision to let myself embrace this moment in time. The decision didn't come easy. I struggle to let myself follow a path different from the one that was so carefully laid out for me. But I'm finding that one of life's most rewarding journeys is walking away from what the world tells us our life should look like, and toward what you truly love - in your own heart. In your own secret soul.

One of my favorite teachers used to say that the best way to get over writer's block, was to write. He taught me that it didn't need to make sense. I didn't have to start at the beginning, stop at the end, or even know where I was going. I just had to start typing. And not stop. The same is true in life. We live such a short existence, and can only experience a fragment of what life has to offer. Sometimes that idea completely overwhelms me, and I stand still, paralyzed by the opportunity cost of every decision, haunted by paths not taken, waiting for others to make decisions for me. But when we stand still, life happens to us, and we become passive bystanders, rather than the authors of our stories. And it‚Äôs always better to write your own story. Even if you don‚Äôt always know what the next chapter holds.

Let's talk about money. How I afford to travel all the time is BY FAR the most common question I get. It‚Äôs a difficult question to answer, for a number of reasons, but primarily because it's based on the false premise that I travel all the time. My Instagram account only shows the most picturesque moments in my life. During those brief moment, I take lots of photographs, and then I post them over time. This creates the illusion that I am always adventuring out in some remote destination. But I'm not. No one is. When I do travel, I'm generally camping, hiking, and road tripping, which are not inherently expensive activities. I started out as a weekend warrior, posting my favorite shots from time spent in the mountains around Seattle. As time passed and my following slowly grew I started to get a few sponsors here and there. And of course that helps. But Instagram is by no means my only source of income. My job is. I guess my point is, you don‚Äôt have to travel the world to experience adventure, nor do you have to spend a ton of money to be a great photographer. Please don't let those temporary limitations keep you from chasing your dreams. The happiest I‚Äôve ever been is when I‚Äôm living in the moment and not comparing myself to the curated version of someone else. Social media is fun, and can be very inspirational, but never forget that it doesn‚Äôt provide a complete picture of anyone's life - only the part they want you to see.

I get asked a lot of questions. But by far the most common question is HOW. And the truth is, I don‚Äôt know. I can‚Äôt answer the how questions, because I don‚Äôt know what I‚Äôm doing, or even where I‚Äôm going most of the time. I‚Äôm still navigating my way through life - and I get lost all the time. I think in the end that‚Äôs the best answer I can give myself, or anyone else. You don‚Äôt need to know exactly how someone else has done whatever it is they are doing. There is no blue print to success because success is a personal journey. You just have to pick a direction and keep moving. After all, if you can see your path laid out in front of you step by step, you know it's not your path. Your own path you make with every step you take. That's why it's yours.
-

I put poison in my eyes this morning. Okay, it was just one eye, and technically it was contact solution - but it turns out the red cap isn‚Äôt just a cute marketing strategy. Anyway, lets just say the burning was intense enough to send me blindly stumbling half clothed back into the shower to try and rip my eyeball out! Once the stinging subsided a little, I pulled myself together, forgot about it, and headed to work. The rest of the morning went smoothly. It was a lovely sunny day, everyone at work was exceptionally friendly, and complete strangers were nice enough to stop and talk to me. It wasn‚Äôt until later, when I wandered past a mirror and saw my eye, that I realized people weren‚Äôt just exceptionally interested in me today - they were concerned! My eye was bright red and swollen. It looked like I‚Äôd been crying for hours. I thought about the irony of having so many caring words directed my way over the course of the day, when in reality I was completely fine. More than fine really, because everyone had been so friendly. It‚Äôs amazing the difference random acts of kindness can make, even if they are misdirected! And it really got me thinking about all of you, and how much all of your amazingly kind and supportive comments, DMs, and emails mean to me on a daily basis. I try to respond to as many as possible, but I know I fall way short, and for that I‚Äôm truly sorry. Please know that I read them all. Your words, wisdom, and art make this crazy often overwhelming world seem so much more approachable, and for that I can't thank you enough!
-
Photo: @itsbigben

The psychology of an obstacle is interesting. For some it‚Äôs an ugly obstruction to be avoided, or removed from existence all together. For others it‚Äôs a challenge to be overcome. And still others don‚Äôt see the obstacle at all. I often wonder, if you never knew something existed in any other form, would you perceive it‚Äôs flaws at all? Or would we just accept it as an organic part of the landscape - as something that adds, rather than detracts from the beauty? I think people work in the same way. Everyone has their obstacles. We can either hide them, or embrace them as challenges to be conquered. But in the end I think personal obstacles are a natural part of the human condition. And when we embrace our differences and grow from the experience, they only add to the beauty of life.

Tonight my home is an Airstream on the Northern California Coast. Laying in bed reading a book and listening to the rain bounce off the metal roof I can‚Äôt help but think about how little we need to be happy. On the bedside table is a copy of Walden. Flipping through the pages I found a familiar passage. Familiar because I have heard it before, and familiar because it so accurately captures my current mood. Anyway, I wanted to share it here: ‚ÄúWe need the tonic of wildness. . . . At the same time that we are earnest to explore and learn all things, we require that all things be mysterious and unexplorable, that land and sea be infinitely wild, unsurveyed and unfathomed by us because unfathomable. We can never have enough of nature. We must be refreshed by the sight of inexhaustible vigor, vast and titanic features, the sea-coast with its wrecks, the wilderness with its living and its decaying trees, the thunder-cloud, and the rain which lasts three weeks and produces freshets. We need to witness our own limits transgressed, and some life pasturing freely where we never wander.‚Äù

Some places always feel like coming home. But for me, home has never been a box with rooms, a yard, and white picket fence.

I tried. I really did. Less than two years ago I spent my days behind a big desk, in a small office, with nothing on the white walls except for the law degree that I thought would be enough. I was restless, couldn't focus, and was definitely not at home.

My home is not a tangible structure, but a feeling. It's on top of a mountain, swimming in an alpine lake, or wandering down a dirt path. That's where all the world's distractions and expectations quietly fade into the distant background and I'm able to finally see the forest past the trees. And it is where I want my story to take place.

Our bus arrived in Jackson, Wyoming in the middle of the night. It was too dark to see anything, but I knew from the itinerary that we must be in the airport parking lot. We stumbled around trying to gather our warm clothes and camera gear without waking the other passengers. Half an hour and a long dirt road later, a taxi dropped us off at a nondescript trail head in the middle of Teton National Park. We raced up the trail, but as the stars faded and the world took on a deep blue hue it became clear we weren't going to make it to the lake for sunrise. Neither of us said anything. We were too tired. Too frustrated. All that faded away as we scrambled up the last section of boulders and the lake came into view. It wasn't what we had wanted. But at that moment, it was everything we needed.

Growing up, I was so focused on traveling as far away as possible that when I was finally able to, I neglected to explore my own backyard. When I returned home from that trip I promised myself that I would focus on the beautiful places right around me. I think it‚Äôs really common to feel like you can‚Äôt have an adventure without spending a ton of money and flying far away. I'm always learning and adjusting to try and find a balance that makes me happy. And that‚Äôs okay. There is no one size fits all path. I think sometimes we feel paralyzed by big decisions because we are taught that life is made up of a linear sequence of events that propels us in a straight line. As a result, it can feel like if we choose one door, then all the alternative paths in life are forever lost to us. But I prefer to think of life as more of a river with numerous distributaries, twist and turns. When it‚Äôs all said and done, the water ends up in more or less the same place, but the path it takes to get there is unique. So take your time, try different things, and remember to trust your own flow.

I studied abroad at a tiny environmental school in Australia for a semester. There were 24 of us in the entire program, and we lived in little huts in the middle of the rainforest up in Northern Queensland. I was so nervous about going. I‚Äôd moved away from home for University, but I‚Äôd never really been alone before. I remember sitting in LAX, my mind racing with excuses to not get on the plane. But when the van finally rounded the last turn on the long dirt road to the school, I looked out over the most beautiful forest I‚Äôd ever seen, and a deep calm washed over me. I‚Äôll never forget that feeling. It was the type of place that makes even the most mundane things become fascinating, remarkable, or otherwise notable. The experience had a profound impact on the way I envisioned my future. Things that had once seemed of the utmost priority didn‚Äôt seem to matter quite as much. When I left Australia I had no idea what I wanted to be when I grew up. But even that didn‚Äôt seem to matter quite as much. What I did know, was that I never wanted to loose that sense of awe that I had left behind with childhood and regained in that forest.

Success is not a limited resource. It means something different to everyone. I think most people‚Äôs idea of success involves achieving some level of happiness - but what brings a person happiness is unique to each individual. No one can steal it, because it belongs only to you. It is the personalized nature of success that makes it both accessible and daunting. Pursuing our own happiness is difficult. It requires sacrifice, hard work, and risk. Under these circumstances it‚Äôs easy to fall into the trap of measuring ourselves against other people‚Äôs definitions of success. But comparing ourselves to others is a slippery slope that generally only rolls one way ‚Äî down hill. I like to think that happiness on the other hand, is found in understanding what you want, pursuing it with all you‚Äôve got, and then taking it from the only person that can give it to you ‚Äî yourself.

You spot it you got it. If we are able to spot admirable qualities in other people, it most likely means we "got it" too. Although these positive attributes might be laying dormant inside us, being able to recognize them in others is the first step toward achieving our own goals. After all, the world outside us is only a reflection of the world inside us. I like to think that means we already have everything we need to become the best version of ourselves - it's just a matter of stoking that internal flame and letting it flourish.

Some things are up to us, and some things are not. To become the best version of ourselves we have to be able to differentiate between the two. Because lets face it; there are only so many hours in the day, and without a way to prioritize our time we can end up drowning in our own goals. Detach from the things you can‚Äôt control, throw your energy into the ones you can, and remember the one thing we can almost always control is our attitude.

The lows in travel, just like in life, help us appreciate the highs. Without them, it‚Äôs easy to take little successes for granted and eventually fail to notice them at all. While the easy road might sound more appealing, I‚Äôve learned that it can also be monotonous. There‚Äôs little to gain, and even less to be learned by coasting along in cruise control. The best laid plans will fall apart, but we don't have to. Instead, we can embrace the lessons that come out of life's lows, and learn to expect the unexpected. At its core photography provides a visual record of a moment in time. But at its best it can provide insight into the world at large in all its stunning diversity. Never stop exploring. There's no end to the things you will see and the experiences we can share.
#alphacollective @sonyalpha

There are some places that are so grand and awe inspiring that they will inevitable make you feel insignificant. And that's a good thing. I once read that the sensation of being a tiny speck in a massive universe might actually make us kinder more generous people by diminishing the emphasis on the individual self. As if I needed another reason to search out places like this! ‚ò∫Ô∏è

Craving a little color in my life.
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Already missing those summer swims. Because let's face it, even if you find some hot springs, it's still freezing when you get out!

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

There should be more outdoor bathtubs. Because this is definitely my favorite way to warm up after a long night in the rain. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Mother nature isn't always pretty. It isn't always comfortable. Its power can even be destructive. But that's okay. Exposure to the elements changes us. It leaves marks on our memory, on our consciousness, on our hearts. It runs in our blood. And if we foster that connection, it can give us perspective and calm amongst the chaos.

As the sun sinks, and the light-ghosts pull back into the forest, you know you could lose everything you ever wanted to lose in this place. You could bury your shadow here.

What we see depends mainly on what we look for. I've been lucky enough to visit Yosemite during every season now, and each time I find myself enchanted by its unique beauty. On this particular trip all of the roads were closed, so I wasn't able to get out of the valley like I had planned. At fist I was pretty bummed because I wanted to explore new locations. But after a couple days at some of my favorite spots, I realized that there are always new things to see, it's just a matter of changing ones perspective.

I've been trying to focus less on results lately. That's not to say I don't go after the things that I want. I do. But I am trying to be open to the possibility that the things I want, don't necessarily come in the same packages that I thought they would or should. I think it's important to try your hardest, but then give yourself permission to be okay with where life takes you. Even if the result doesn't conform with your expectations, it may be closer to what you actually want than you realize. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

When in LA! üòâ 
When we started up the trail to this view point I didn't think there was any way we would make it before the sunset, but this was one of those special times when the colors just won't quit! Thanks @asenseofhuber for helping me check this one off my bucket list, and @everchanginghorizon for capturing the moment! #LostInLA #DiscoverLA

I had the opportunity to @discoverLA last week and I was floored by all the natural beauty. From the beaches to the hills I couldn't have asked for more. Special thanks to @asenseofhuber for showing me around. Check out his feed for a sweet video of all the places we explored! #LostInLA 
Photo: @asenseofhuber

Alberta has more glacier lakes than I've ever seen in one place. But I totally get it, if I was Alberta I'd make sure I could stare at myself all the time too. üòâ @travelalberta #explorealberta 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Wilderness is an idea separate and bigger than any tangible place. It is an island in time - with nothing to date it on the calendar of humanity. Out there, in those places that make us feel small, you can look backward into the ages and forward into the unknown. Time stops, and you can feel the weight of eternity. Ideas have a life of their own. Find your wilderness, and breath it in.
Moving to Yosemite. Permanently. That's a thing right? üòâ
It's so difficult to capture the hidden spirit of the wilderness. And yet so easy for it to capture us.

Sometimes you show up for a sunset and you get handed a snow storm. And when that happens, I find the best way to stay warm is to laugh it off. ‚ùÑÔ∏èüòã Thanks for capturing the moment @everchanginghorizon.

Don't let perfect be the enemy of good. I can't tell you how many times the fear of failing, or just not being the best at something, has prevented me from trying at all. In other words, how many times I've let my idea of perfect steal away my good. Now I realize the memories made while trying - even if you end up failing - are much better than no memories at all. @travelalberta #explorealberta

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Sometimes the journey is the destination. But sometimes the destination really is the destination. So when you finally get there, don't rush it - slow down and take time to reflect on your surroundings. A place is rarely the same more than once, especially if you focus on the details.

Jumping in puddles and playing in the rain this past week really brought back some good childhood memories. Living in Seattle I'm used to wet grey weather, but it's usually an excuse to stay inside and wait for the storm to pass. I'm thinking this winter I might just have to throw it back and spend more time dancing in the rain! ‚ò∫Ô∏è @muckbootco #muckboots #sharemymucks #partner

I just got home after an amazing week exploring southern Alberta. There weren't a lot of sunsets or sunrises, and the fall colors were all gone. But there also weren't any lines, traffic, or people - and conditions don't get much better than that! @travelalberta #explorealberta

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

node.text: I snuck up into the mountains last week to take advantage of the weather before the storms rolled in. It may have been sunny up there, but fall was definitely in the air ‚Äì as well as a little snow! Luckily I had my new @camelbak bottle with me, so I was able to stay nice and toasty with some piping hot tea while taking in the views. Mountains and hot beverages ‚Äì can‚Äôt ask for much more than that! #GotYourBak

Alone in the wilderness, walking among these ancient giants, I am reminded of how small I am, how tiny all my troubles are, how little time I have existed and will continue to exist. The universe is limitless and I'm acutely aware of my insignificance. The forest gives my life perspective, and I can almost hear the trees welcoming me into their world. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon
Waking up just to dream a little bit more.

Sometimes people ask me if I would keep writing if there was no one on the other end reading. I have no way of knowing really, but I hope so. If no one was reading, there would probably be some darker stuff mixed in with the positive. But I‚Äôm not sure that would be very productive. My captions are as much for me as anyone that happens to be reading them. They are my way of taking control over my personal story. There is something about writing down my thoughts that makes them real. I don‚Äôt want to pretend that life is all peaches and cream - it's not. But the process of writing my stories with a positive spin has fundamentally changed the way I approach life. I choose to focus on the silver lining, because in the end that‚Äôs what I‚Äôd rather spend my energy on - in writing and life.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I spent last weekend trying to soak in as much fall as I could find. At first I struggled, but with every passing hour the air seemed to get a little crisper, the leaves a little brighter, and before I knew it the world was a kaleidoscope of colors floating around me. The whole experience made me pretty grateful for Octobers. üòäüçÇüçÅ

node.text:
We live such a short existence, and can only experience a fragment of what life has to offer. Sometimes this idea completely overwhelms me, and I stand still, paralyzed by the idea of all the paths not taken. But I'm slowly learning that maybe the path doesn't matter. To be truly present and enjoy the path that I'm currently on is the real accomplishment.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Day dreaming about this place and scheming ways to get back. Always. Where's that one place that's always calling to you? I want to hear about the destinations and experiences that captured your imagination  and stole a little piece of your heart! Those are the places that stay with us long after we've returned home. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

There's nothing quite like waking up in the mountains. The crisp fresh air, the warmth of first light, and dreamy views - it all just makes you feel a little more alive. Excited to head up into the mountains tonight. Hope everyone has a great Sunday and I'll see you tomorrow! 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I grew up in a city, and I‚Äôve really never known much else. But every summer when I was little, my parents would take me to visit my grandparents on their ranch down in Reno. I loved it. The ranch, and my grandparents have been gone for a long time now, but the dirt roads, dry air, wide open spaces, and long stories over Arnold Palmers will always stay with me. As will my distrust of horses! But seeing them reminds me of those summers - and that‚Äôs always a good thing.

Last polar plunge of the season. (Maybe) üòâ

@sonyalpha #alphacollective

I've always been drawn to water, and find that being in, on or under water is strangely comforting. Water helps me to relax, and experience a sense of connectedness that I rarely feel elsewhere. The nice thing about water, is that it's everywhere. I can't always be chasing down the next alpine lake, so it has been important for me to find those moments of calm in everyday life. It can be as simple as a paddle at the park, or the sound of rain on my window, as long as I'm open to it. Where is your happy place? 
@evolve_boards

A couple weeks ago I had the opportunity to fly over the Teton Range. The mountains were beautiful, but I was hypnotized by the way the rivers and streams twisted their way through the landscape. I was struck by how abstract it looked - like black water coursing through earth's veins. The experience reminded me that perspective is everything. Our perception of reality is malleable. It is always shifting. We can't control every outcome in life, but we always have the power to change the way we think about them.

If home is where the heart is, my home is located somewhere in between here and there, beyond the shallows, floating in that place that gives life depth. My heart belongs to a feeling. It's often fleeting, always illusive, and impossible to define. But there's no mistaking when it hits.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Caught up in the way it made me feel. 
Searching for icebergs at Iceburg Lake in Glacier National Park. üòâüí¶ Photo: @everchanginghorizon

There's a completeness in nature that always has a calming effect on me. It's the one place where I don't find myself searching for more. Nothing is perfect, and yet everything has its place. 
@sonyalpha #alphacollective

I grew up with a pretty clear idea of what life should look like. That "should" dictated every decision I made - whether I realized it or not. Then one day, all of the building blocks I had carefully balanced to create a life in line with what others expected of me started to topple over. Confused and lost, I fell back on hiking and camping - interests that I had long abandoned. For the first time in years I decided I had time to join my brother on a backpacking trip. Little did I know at the time that that trip would be the first building block in my new life. I'm not exactly sure what this new life looks like because there are no "shoulds" anymore. I still feel lost all the time. I question where I'm going, and sometimes wish I still had a blue print. But this time around my building blocks are made out of dreams, aspirations, and goals I set for myself, rather than for other people. So even if things don't always work out, I know at least I'll have a strong foundation.  #ConqueringFrontiers

I want to stand as close to the edge as possible without going over. Out on the edge you see all sorts of things you can't see from the center. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon
I'm not a morning person, but there's just something about watching the sunrise that I can't resist. The FOMO is strong with me.  @sonyalpha #alphacollective

Art is the deception that helps us realize the truth. It has no boundaries. It is whatever you want it to be. And it's beautiful because it's a reflection of the person that created it. The last few days I've had the pleasure of road tripping with some amazing photographers and @sonyalpha. Getting to know everyone better through their art has been a true honor. #alphacollective

I learn a lot about myself when I spend extended periods of time in the outdoors. One of the best lessons nature has taught me is how to listen. Sometimes the hardest part about listening is being quiet. And I don't just mean closing your mouth. True quiet requires silencing your mind. Refusing to engage with the doubt, worry, and judgment that can dominate our inner monologues. Only when I achieve that inner quiet am I able to truly listen to the world around me.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

There are multiple sides to every story. Even your favorite ones. 
Taking in a new side of Half Dome. üòä

Let‚Äôs talk about money. Not because I want to, but because I know it‚Äôs the elephant in the room for a lot of people. The answer to how I fund my travels has a lot of moving parts, and I‚Äôll try my best to be as open about those as possible. But first, a word about social media. My Instagram account is a carefully curated collection of photographs from my outdoor adventures. It does not represent my life ‚Äì just some of the more picturesque moments. During those brief moments I take lots of photographs, and then I post them over time. Currently most of my life is spent working as a real estate agent in Seattle. Real estate works for me right now because although I put in a lot of hours, my day to day schedule is relatively flexible. Previous to working in real estate, I was a lawyer. As an attorney I made more money, but had a lot less control over my time. I was unable to find the balance that I wanted in my life as a lawyer, so I reevaluated my priorities and made a change. Do I think everyone can or should make a big career change? No. Do I think most of us have room in our lives to make more time for the things we truly want? Yes. Can that be scary, hard, daunting? Most definitely. I realize that I promised a caption about money, and then talked forever about time. But the two are impossible to separate, and while money will come and go, time only passes.

Transitions in life can be scary. But whenever I worry about making a big change I  remember that some of the most beautiful times in nature occur during periods of transition. Life wouldn't have the same magic without sunrises, fall colors, and the way the earth smells right after a storm. Just like nature, it's in the transitions that we find opportunity, growth, and ourselves. @albionfit 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

You're allowed to free yourself from your own expectations. You might be surprised where your wings can take you when they aren't tethered to outcomes. Have an awesome Sunday everyone! 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Happy birthday to the @nationalparkservice! Here's to our next 100 together! üòâ üéà#NPS100

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I get asked a lot about how I find the time to travel. I never know how to answer that question, because the truth is, I'm not sure I do find the time. Usually when the question is asked I resort to talking about priorities and balance. And I think in a lot of ways that's the best advice I can give. But by no means have I found that balance in my own life. Lately I've been getting pretty lost in the details. I struggle to remember what the big picture looks like, and I'm not even sure where I want to go. But that's what adventure is all about. You can't always be at the summit looking down. Sometimes your path will take you through the forest up endless switchbacks, and you just have to trust that there's a view at the top.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Keep your head in the clouds and dream on. The sky is not the limit. It's just the view. ‚ò∫Ô∏è .

Photo: @everchanginghorizon
Headed up into the mountains tomorrow. Pretty excited to see what I can see! I've been waiting a long time for this one. üôä

#TravelMeans embracing the unexpected. In life and travel you can‚Äôt always control your circumstances, but you can control how you react to them. Not everything is what it appears to be, and even the best laid plans fall apart. Travel means growing from every experience‚Äîexpected or unexpected‚Äîand recognizing that every place has a story worth telling.

What does travel mean to you? Share your story with @Janbala using #TravelMeans.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Excited to head out on a new adventure with old friends today. Cruising through Idaho, not sure what I'll find, but that's how all good adventures start. If you've got any can't miss spots let me know. Have backpack, will hike! üòâ

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I can think of few things I'd rather do on a hot summer Sunday than binge-watch a waterfall from the best seat in the house. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I've been watching a lot of the History Channel show "Alone" lately before bed. It makes for some pretty interesting dreams, but on a more practical side it has me thinking a lot about wilderness survival. The survivalists in the show face inclement weather, big predators, hunger, and other challenges on a daily basis; but they all seem to struggle the most with the psychological effects of just being alone. When I'm alone with no distractions, I have no choice but to listen to my own thoughts. And that can be a scary thing. The stories we tell ourselves have a lot of power. Make your survival story a positive one!

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

A few years ago I backpacked The Narrows with my mom. And like all adventures I take my mom on, it did not go as smoothly as planned. Highlights included forgetting to tell her that The Narrows is full of water, hiking through the night with only one working headlamp and one set of trekking polls between the two of us, missing our camp spot, hitch hiking back to our car, and the crazy person screaming in the distance all night long (only my mom heard that part). But practice makes perfect, and this time I was a lot more prepared. Although I still had to learn the wet way that the shortest distance between two points is not always the fastest. üòâ

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

There's clarity in simplicity. This is true in photography, writing, and life. But in a frantic hyperconnected world distractions come easy, while clarity is often illusive. Nature has the ability to put life into perspective in a way very few things can. We are part of nature, and yet it has complete control. It's that simple. And when I'm out there, when everything else is stripped away, it's always a little easier to see things clearly.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Be content with what you have; rejoice in the way things are. When you realize nothing's lacking, the whole world belongs to you. [Lao Tsu] // Chasing sunsets in Zion. And I wouldn't have it any other way.
Meet me in the woods. I'll be right here. ‚ò∫Ô∏è

When I first moved to Seattle, it was so quiet at night that I couldn't sleep. The silent nights have grown on me, but I will always be drawn to places where darkness is ushered in by the pulsating glow of fireflies and the hypnotizing sound of a million creatures chirping lullabies to each other. Give me a tree house in the middle of it all, and I might never leave. ‚ò∫Ô∏è

Some places are known for iconic visuals. But the places that stick with me long after I've returned home are the ones that catch me off guard by highjacking all my senses and captivating my imagination. These are the places that demand attention to the details. Places where the air, people, and tea are all just a little bit sweeter, and adventure is just around the river bend. 
#floridasplayground #historicmilton
The lookouts down here might not be on top of mountains, but I can't argue with the views! üòâ

My first morning in Navarre, I beat the sun to the beach. I stood waist deep in the warm water, a half mile of empty white sand on either side of me, and watched as the sun slid up over the horizon. Just as I was about to grab my camera from the beach I saw them. A pair of dolphins slowly dancing through the shallows right in front of me. I can't remember the last time I was so caught up in the magic of a moment. But I know I won't forget that one anytime soon. 
#floridasplayground #navarrebeach #sp

Life is a balance of holding on and letting go. And while I think most people struggle with the letting go part of the balancing act, I find that holding on can be just as difficult. It's so easy to get distracted with all the little details life throws at us that sometimes I forget to hold on to the big picture. Here's to letting go of things when they get to heavy, and holding on with all we've got to the things that make us happy.

Dreams demand hustle. Few things worth having come effortlessly, but in a world where we are constantly comparing ourselves to other people's highlight reels it can be difficult to manage our expectations appropriately. We fall into the trap of believing that life is somehow simpler for others. It's never that simple. Dreams are meant to be chased. 
Photo:@everchanginghorizon

I spent my Independence Day in the place I feel most free, taking in some mountains majesty, and logging footsteps on my @bellabeat. üòâ

Happy 4th everyone!

Humbled in the cool shade of these silent giants.

node.text: For as long as I can remember I‚Äôve had a real talent for losing things. I‚Äôve gotten better with time, but you probably shouldn‚Äôt loan me your favorite sweatshirt, and you definitely shouldn‚Äôt give me your phone or keys ‚Äì not even for a minute. Growing up some chose to view this rather endearing character flaw as a negative. I chose to look at it as a constant source of important life lessons ‚Äì memories over stuff, nothing lasts forever, etc. Nevertheless, I was pretty excited when @ablyapparel sent me one of their magic odor and stain resistant shirts. While not impossible, ‚Äãturns out ‚Äãit‚Äôs a lot harder to lose a shirt you never need to take off! üòâ

Time has a wonderful way of showing us what matters. Don't waste it on things you already know the answer to. Just dive in!

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Making decisions and implementing change has always been difficult for me. I think in large part this is because conventional wisdom tells us that once you choose a door, all the doors leading to other options and opportunities close. For me, that idea is paralyzing. Perhaps the most useful lesson I have learned from nature is that nothing needs to last forever. We are free to choose one direction and then change course at any point. You can travel down a path all the way to its conclusion, or head back to the trailhead when you have achieved your personal goal. We do not live in a static reality where you only get one door. So if you choose the wrong one, shut it, and try again.  #danielwellington 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

They say that home is where the heart is, and from the time I could walk my Dad fostered a love for the outdoors in me. I can't thank him enough for making sure that no matter where life takes me, I'll always have a home to go to that doesn't cost a thing, and no one can take away. Happy Father's Day Dad! .
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I got into some poison oak last week, and my skin is super angry about the whole thing. I tried to apologize by feeding it Benadryl and massaging it with creams, but it's having none of that. If only I was back at this place, I could dunk it in water so cold it would forget all about the poison oak incident, and we could both just lay back and enjoy the brain freeze. üòâ
.
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Travel can be transformative. But that is primarily because it has a way of pushing us outside our comfort zone, not because of the distance covered. A few years ago I stopped counting passport stamps and started looking for opportunities to expand my horizons closer to home. I quickly discovered that I don't need to go far to find places that take my breath away.
Stacked. üôå

Got real lost and made a lot of hot chocolate this weekend. So basically I got everything I wanted. üòâ
.
Photo by @everchanginghorizon

Recently my default speed has been pretty break neck. I always want to see and experience as many places as possible when I travel. But on my most recent road trip a variety of circumstances conspired to slow the pace -  it turned out to be just what I needed. Taking the time to be truly present, smell the flowers, and just sit and watch the world slowly change around me was a great reminder of why I started retreating to the outdoors in the first place.

Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Talking to the trees. 
I frequently catch myself personifying trees. I give them human characteristics, individual personalities, and imagine them whispering epic stories to each other through the wind. I'm certainly not the first person to cast trees in a human light. And if you stand real still and listen to the trees in the middle of the Redwoods it's hard not to believe that there might be something behind all the lore. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon
Be patient with yourself. Nothing in nature blooms all year. üåº‚úåÔ∏è

The truth is, comparing ourselves to others doesn't just steal our joy, it robs us of our creativity. Comparison prevents us from embracing those things that are uniquely ours. I like to think of life as a piece of art that you create through inspiration, vision, and time. And if your life is a piece of art, why be an inferior reproduction when you're an original? 
Thanks to @albionfit for making life even prettier with their performance wear. #iamalbionfit

When I was little my favorite babysitter went to Hawaii on vacation, met a guy that lived in a treehouse, fell in love, and moved into the trees with him. I got to go visit her once and I fell in love too - but with the treehouse, not the guy! So I was pretty stoked when I got to make this one my home, even if it was just for a day. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

Sunrise ridge hikes up into the clouds. That's usually how I know I'm still dreaming. But this time I was wide awake. 
Photo: @everchanginghorizon

I'm a list maker, and lately I've been working on my summer bucket list. Wondering how it compares to other people's. You never know, maybe we'll run into each other - it's a pretty small Instagram world. üòâ

While we can't control how many moments we have left in this life, we do have some control over how we spend them and who we spend them with. I can't seem to spend enough moments in this place. It looks different every time I go, but it's always beautiful, and always leaves me wanting more.

"It's a terrible thing, I think, in life to wait until you're ready. I have this feeling now that actually no one is ever ready to do anything. There is almost no such thing as ready. There is only now. And you may as well do it now. Generally speaking, now is as good a time as any." - Hugh Laurie

There are some no good things in this world. But there's also hot chocolate, marshmallows, and mountain sunsets. Just remember that.

I've only been to Yosemite in the winter. And while I have no doubt that it's a magical place any time of year, there is something truly special about having some of the most iconic views out there all to yourself. It's almost enough to make me forget how cold it gets! üòâ

We are always taught not to care what other people think. But the thing is, we do care. It's human. And being human is generally a good thing. Don't let what other people think define you. And by all means embrace the positive and let go of the negative. All I'm saying, is don't beat yourself up for caring. It doesn't make you weak. It makes you a person. And that's a beautiful thing.

Doing my best Mowgli impression. üòâ

This past week in the Dominican Republic I had the privilege of teaching English with @fathomtravel, and I have no doubt that I learned more from the experience than the students learned from me.

Growing up there was not a lot of diversity in my life. Although I was not consciously aware of it, for the most part I was surrounded by people with similar backgrounds. I love looking through the photo albums at my parent‚Äôs house when I go home. In many of the pictures, my parents are hiking to beautiful places with my brother and I bouncing around in their backpacks or toddling up a trail at their sides. Whenever I see these pictures I think about how much easier it would have been to leave us at home ‚Äì after all we could barely walk. But I‚Äôm so grateful that they didn‚Äôt. Even though I don‚Äôt necessarily remember these excursions into the great outdoors, I now realize that my parents were giving me my happy place. That place that will always be there to ground me when I feel myself drifting away from the person I am, and the person I want to become. 
Unfortunately, a lot of kids don't have these same opportunities. That's why my friend @erinoutdoors is working with @bornwildproject to inspire more outdoor family time. If you've got a minute, check them out. They've got a Kickstarter campaign and lots of sweet adventure gear to give away! #Gear2GetWild

We don't have an infinite number of days on this planet. And while we can't control how many moments we have left, we do have some control over how we spend them. Choices have always been inherently difficult for me - and the decision to be happy is no exception. But ultimately it is a choice. Happiness will not come to you. It must come from you. ‚ò∫Ô∏è‚úåÔ∏è Photo: @everchanginghorizon

There are some places that are so grand in scale that they will inevitably make you feel insignificant. And that's a good thing! I once read that the sensation of being a tiny speck in a massive universe might actually make you a kinder more generous person by diminishing the emphasis on the individual self. And after spending the weekend exploring Arizona with @christianannschaffer, @taylormichaelburk, and @everchanginghorizon, I'm convinced it's true. I couldn't have asked for a nicer crew to experience some of this planet's most awe inspiring landscapes with! üòä

node.text:
One of my favorite movies when I was little was Robin Hood. You know, the animated version where Robin Hood is a fox and Little John is a bear. Anyway, at some point in the movie Robin Hood whisks Maid Marian off into the woods, where they are suddenly surrounded by glowing fireflies.  Maybe it was this scene, maybe it was the strikingly similar scene in The Little Mermaid, or maybe it's just that I loved bugs when I was a kid, but I've always really wanted to see some fireflies in action. 
I'm in North Carolina this week, and it feels like the type of place that fireflies might call home. No luck yet, but I'm crossing my fingers. Hope y'all have a magical weekend!

The last time I went cliff jumping I landed in a perfect seated position. Hard. I had no idea that the jump had not gone according to plan until I surfaced, and everyone was just staring at me, and asking if I was okay. Apparently, my less than graceful entry made a pretty amazing sound. Lucky for me, there was also a GoPro involved, so I didn't have to take everyone else's word for it. Bonus - everyone got to enjoy my water landing over, and over, and over again. Cherry on top - I got to repeatedly explain why my backside looked like I'd just gone through some pretty intense hazing for the rest of the trip! I haven't jumped off anything since, but this place made me think about it. üòâ

Finally got a chance to get back up into the mountains this weekend. It was short, but sweet! And just what I needed. 
Also excited to be joining the @briskoutdoors community as an adventurer! They have a beautiful page full of yummy outdoor adventure inspiration. If you're like me, and already day dreaming about your next exploit, head on over and check them out! üòä

When I was little I was really fascinated with clouds‚Äîespecially the type that you could walk around on, and sleep in. Accordingly, I decided that the best thing to do would be to get a little chunk of cloud all for myself. The plan was to wait until the next time my family flew somewhere, and then when no one was looking, roll down the window, and grab a fist full of cloud to sneak into my bag. It was by all accounts a flawlessly conceived covert mission. So imagine my disappointment when the day finally came, and there was no way to roll down my window! I remember thinking it made sense. If you could roll down airplane windows, everyone would probably steal the clouds! Although unforeseen obstacles ultimately foiled my plan, today I‚Äôm glad they keep those clouds protected from greedy airplane passengers like me. Otherwise there might not be views like this to enjoy!

The trail was hot, winding, and long, and just when the girl began to give up hope, they broke out of the trees and were greeted by the stunning azure waters of their final destination - fabled Blanca Lake. And it was then, that the puppy lost his F'n mind! His Shepard instincts wouldn't  allow him to let any of the other hikers at the lake stray into the water, and when the girl tried to go for a swim he nearly drowned her in an ill conceived rescue attempt. And then there was the barking. The crazy, wild, incessant barking.  The girl was so rattled  that she fled deep into the forest, and back to the parking lot. And so, like this story, the girl and her puppy's time at the lake was cut tragically short.
